Ōzono Kofun was located on the northwestern terrace of the {{ill|Shinodayama Hills|ja|信太山丘陵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} in southern Osaka. The site was excavated in 1974 and 1976 by the Osaka Prefectural Board of Education and Takaishi City Board of Education. The mound was subsequently destroyed, leaving no visible remains.<ref name="Ōzono Kofun (Kofun)">Matsumura, Takafumi. "Ōzono Kofun," in {{ill|Comprehensive Dictionary of Japanese Kofun|ja|日本古墳大辞典|1=Comprehensive Dictionary of Japanese Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, Tokyo-do Publishing, 1989.</ref>

The tumulus had a short-fronted {{ill|Scallop Kofun|ja|帆立貝形古墳|1=Scallop Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} type.<ref name="Ōzono Kofun (Kofun)" /> While the mound was already flattened by the time of excavation, its area were estimated as follows: total length approximately 53 meters (or possibly 57 meters<ref name="Explanation Board">Intypeational sign.</ref>), rear circular section diameter about 34 meters, and front section width about 25 meters.<ref name="Ōzono Kofun (Kofun)" /> The surface of the mound featured {{ill|Fukiishi|ja|葺石|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Haniwa|ja|埴輪|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}, some of which were recovered from the surrounding moat.<ref name="Ōzono Kofun (Kofun)" /> Among the haniwa, various types were identified, including cylindrical, house-shaped, human-shaped, horse-shaped, chicken-shaped, grass skirt-shaped, shield-shaped, quiver-shaped, lid-shaped, and sword-shaped varieties.<ref name="Ōzono Kofun (Kofun)" /> The moat surrounding the mound was approximately 3–4 meters wide.<ref name="Ōzono Kofun (Kofun)" /> The burial chamber remains unknown due to the mound's destruction.

Ōzono Kofun is believed to have been constructed in the late [[5th century]] during the middle {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name="Ōzono Kofun (Kofun)" /><ref name="Izumi Northern Lineage"/> The surrounding Ōzono archaeological site is recognized as a significant settlement from the Kofun period, featuring a large number of pillar-supported buildings. Ōzono Kofun is identified as the burial site of a local chief. In northern Izumi, chief tombs are divided into two groups—northern and southern—and appear to alternate in their leadership roles, with Ōzono Kofun being part of this rotational system.<ref name="Izumi Northern Lineage"/><ref>"Ōzono Site Excavation Report - Survey of the Kuzunohana District," Izumi City Board of Education, 2014, pp. 1–4.</ref>
<gallery>
File:大園古墳出土 埴輪 鶏.JPG|Haniwa (chicken)<br>{{small|Exhibited at the {{ill|Osaka Prefectural Chikatsu Asuka Museum|ja|大阪府立近つ飛鳥博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=draft}}.}}
